<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-084-980  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 084 980.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Jan 22 1990 v9 n2 p50(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Xerox integrates 2 text products. (Xerox Corp.'s Viewpointdocument processing software and Information Dimensions Inc.'sBasis text information management system) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taft, Darryl K.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Xerox Corp. Integrated Systems Operations (product introduction)Information Dimensions Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Xerox Document Search and Retrieval (Computer program) (productintroduction)Basis (data base management system) (product enhancement)ViewPoint (Project management software) (product enhancement).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionIntegrated SoftwareData Base Management SystemsEthernet.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Xerox Integrates 2 Text ProductsandM;Xerox Corp. has announced information retrieval software that lets usersfile, retrieve and perform complex searches for compound documents, includingboth text and graphics, without knowing a query language and with minimalkeystroking.andM;The software, called Xerox Document Search and Retrieval (DSR), integratesXerox's Viewpoint document processing software and user interface withInformation Dimensions Inc.'s Basis text information management software.andM;Xerox Integrated Systems Operations, Sunnyvale, Calif., designed DSR toperform complex, unstructured data searches, particularly when rapid and easyaccess to large volumes of text-based information is required, companyofficials said.andP;  Users access the system through the Xerox Network System andremote access workstations.andM;When used with the Basis software, DSR can identify a single word in aone-million-document database, roughly the equivalent of 2.5 million pages,within three to seven seconds, company officials said.andP;  The speed dependsupon network traffic and the number of users on the host computer.andM;Potential users of the new product include government, aerospace, legal,health, transportation or insurance enterprises that have high volumecompound document filing, search, retrieval and distribution requirements,and a need for archival storage requiring frequent search for and referenceto filed documents.andM;DSR helps users store and retrieve original text documents, includinggraphics and footnotes contained within the document, without losing thedocument's properties or characteristics, company officials said.andM;Users also may search for documents by specifying words, phrases orparameters such as who created it, when it was created, or who it was sentto.andP;  DSR also lets users share documents among multiple authors and readers.andM;DSR lets users store documents received or created in a variety of forms,including those generated from electronic mail, word processing and scannedor disk input.andM;DSR will be available from Xerox for users with ViewPoint software, Xerox6085 workstations, Ethernet local area networks, and a DEC/VAX computerrunning Information Dimensions' Basis software.andP;  DSR will be available in thefirst quarter of 1990.andM;DSR pricing starts at $10,000 for 10 user nodes.andP;  The license price includesthe specified number of desktop nodes, an environmental analysis, trainingfor the user's Xerox Network System systems administrator and VAX systemmanager, user and administrator documentation, and all of the necessary DSRsoftware for the Xerox 6085 workstations and the DEC VAX computer runningBasis software.andM;Contact Xerox's Barbara E. Burke, tel.andP;  213-333-3613.andO;</TEXT></DOC>